SIMPLE: ironclad
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ironclad
<hw>I"ron*clad`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Clad
in iron; protected or covered with iron, as a vessel for naval
warfare.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Rigorous; unbreakable; severe; exacting; inflexible;
<as>as, an <ex>ironclad</ex> oath or pledge</as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ironclad</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ironclad
<hw>I"ron*clad`</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A naval vessel having the parts
above water covered and protected by iron or steel usually in large
plates closely joined and made sufficiently thick and strong to resist
heavy shot. Modern naval vessels are made of steel throughout, and this
term is only used in historical contexts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ironclad</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Ironclad
<hw>I"ron*clad`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>having an outer
covering of iron or steel; <as>as, an <ex>ironclad</ex> war
vessel</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>so strong or secure as to be unbreakable; <as>as, an
<ex>ironclad</ex> contract</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>irones</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>irone</ent>⟦br⟧
